# Per-project airlock config — commit this at <project>/.airlock/config.
#
# SAFE-PARSED as `key = value` (never executed). Unknown keys are ignored;
# values are validated. Only these keys are honored:

# Extra environment-built directories to keep container-local, ADDED to the
# default ".venv node_modules". Relative paths only (absolute paths and ".."
# are rejected). Use for monorepos / non-standard layouts.
# artifact_dirs = venv frontend/node_modules backend/.venv

# Extra egress domains this project needs, ADDED to whatever the project's egress
# posture already allows. Domain characters only. Because this file is writable from
# INSIDE the sandbox, each domain must be APPROVED once on the host: you're prompted
# at launch, and approved domains apply silently thereafter. An unexpected domain
# here (e.g. added by a compromised session) prompts and is skipped unless you
# approve it. Approvals live host-side where the box can't reach.
# Entries may be separated by spaces or commas, and each one may be a hostname, a
# bare IPv4 (reachable on 443 only), an IPv6 literal, or "IPv4:port" for a datasource
# on a non-standard port (e.g. VictoriaMetrics on 8428) -- that form opens exactly
# that one host+port and nothing else. An entry that matches none of those shapes is
# a typo and ABORTS the launch: a grant that can never apply would otherwise leave
# the box looking configured while silently having no access.
# egress = cdn.jsdelivr.net fonts.gstatic.com
# egress = 10.1.15.115:8428, 10.1.15.116:8428

# NOT configurable here: the egress POSTURE. By default a project gets 'minimal' —
# Anthropic core only, plus the `egress =` domains above. To also open package
# registries, run one of these on the HOST: `airlock egress dev` (npm+PyPI+GitHub),
# or a subset like `airlock egress github pypi` (GitHub+PyPI, no npm). Like secrets,
# this is a host-controlled grant kept out of this box-writable file, so a compromised
# session can't widen its own egress to the registries.

# Extra folders this project needs to see, e.g. a sibling repo whose docs or code it
# references. Paths are RELATIVE to the host's AIRLOCK_SHARE_BASE (default ~/development)
# — so this committed file never contains absolute /home paths, and a path can't escape
# the base (absolute and ".." are rejected). Like egress, each folder is APPROVED ONCE
# on the host: you're prompted at launch, and approved folders mount silently thereafter
# at their real host path. Approvals live host-side where the box can't reach, so an
# unexpected share added by a compromised session just prompts and is skipped.
#   share    = <relpath> ...   -> READ-ONLY  (the default, least privilege)
#   share_rw = <relpath> ...   -> READ-WRITE (the box can MODIFY those files)
# Read and write use separate approvals, and the write prompt says so explicitly:
# approving a read share never grants write. Prefer `share` unless the box genuinely
# needs to write the folder.
# share = other-repo virtualization-mcp-servers/deploy
# share_rw = virtualization-application-registry

# Image/stack to run for this project. MUST be a claude-airlock:* tag (you can't
# point the sandbox at an arbitrary image from here).
# image = claude-airlock:dev

# NOT configurable here: secrets. Manage them with `airlock secret set KEY VALUE`
# (or `KEY pass:PATH` to resolve from your password store at launch, encrypted at
# rest). It's a host-controlled store the box can neither read nor choose from;
# it's injected as env, and your committed .mcp.json / configs reference it by
# name (e.g. ${MCP_HUB_TOKEN}). Keep injected creds read-only/scoped.
